<a href="plate1.gif">Plate 1. <em>(374Kbytes)</em></a>
This image of Manu National Park, Peru was acquired on June 7, 1993 by the
J-ERS-1 SAR.  In the center of the image, the Madre de Dios River flows from
the West to the East, eventually joining the Amazon river.<p>
<p>
<a href="plate2.jpg">Plate 2. <em>(1.8Mbytes)</em></a>   This Manu National Park, Peru mosaic of AIRSAR synoptically
processed L-band HH polarization data corresponds to the JERS-1 image acquired
on the same date (see plate 1).The image was made from seven flight lines by
AIRSAR.  Five of the flight lines were ascending paths looking toward the West,
while two were decending passes looking toward the East.    Each swath has
incidence angles varying from 10 degrees to 60 degrees.  The natural falloff in
backscatter values with range was not removed.  The rivers flow downstream from
the West to the East, and eventually meet with the Amazon river.  The largest
river in the image is the Madre de Dios.  At the far left of the image is the
Manu river, which meets the Madre de Dios river near the village of Boca Manu.
<p>
<p>
<a href="plate3.jpg">Plate 3. <em>(544Kbytes)</em></a>  This  color mosaic of AIRSAR Three frequency (C-band, HH
polarization;  L-band HH polarization;  P-band HH polarization) data follows
the Manu River upstream from the Madre de Dios River.  CHH is assigned the
color blue, LHH is assigned the color green, and PHH is assigned the color red.
Incidence angle varies between 10 degrees on the South side of the swath to 60
degrees on the North side.  The natural falloff in backscatter values with
range was not removed.  <p>
<p>
<a href="plate4.gif">Plate 4. <em>(3.0Mbytes)</em></a>
JERS-1 image of the Rosamond calibration array at Edwards Air Force
Base, California.  This image was acquired on April 30, 1993.  Six corner
reflectors are visible in the center of the image, though one is faint.<p>
<p>
<a href="plate5.gif">Plate 5. <em>(2.0Mbytes)</em></a>
Images of the Rosamond calibration array at Edwards Air Force Base,
California was acquired by AIRSAR on May 18, 1993.  Three channels are shown.
Seven corner reflectors are visible in the dry lake bed.<p>
