<TITLE>SRL-1 Mission Update</TITLE>
<H1>SRL-1 Mission Update </H1>
<HR>
<hr>
<p>In April, 1994, The Space Shuttle Endeavour successfully launched into
orbit 
carrying the Space Radar Laboratory (SRL-1). 
 SRL-1 consists primarily of <a href="desc/SIRCdesc.html">SIR-C/X-SAR</a>
 , which are imaging radars
that are being used to study the Earth.
</P>
<HR>
<p><strong>***The following mission data is available <em>only</em> here
and is subject to change.  It should not be confused with official 
images and/or press releases from the JPL Public Information Office.
If you have any questions about the material presented here, contact 
<a href="feedback.html">me (not the JPL PIO office)!</a> ***</strong>
<p></p>
<ul>
<li><a href="srl1/ground.html">Ground measurements at Death Valley, California</a></li> 
<li><a href="srl1/dataproc.html">Status of data processing</a></li>
</ul>
<p>
<strong>Optical views from STS-59</strong> are <a
href="http://images.jsc.nasa.gov/html/sts59.htm">now available from JSC</a>
 </p>
<p>
