<TITLE>SRL-2 Mission Update</TITLE>
<H1>SRL-2 Mission Update </H1>
<HR>
<p>The Space Shuttle successfully launched on <strong>September 30, 1994
</strong>, carrying the 
Space Radar Laboratory (SRL-2) into orbit 
once again.  SRL-2 consists primarily of <a href="desc/SIRCdesc.html">SIR-C/X-SAR</a>
 , which are imaging radars
that are being used to study the Earth.
</p><p>This mission of the Endeavour ended after an 11 day
mission on Tuesday October 11, 1994.</p>
<P>
</P>
<HR>
<p><strong>***The following mission data is available <em>only</em> here
and is subject to change.  It should not be confused with official 
images and/or press releases from the JPL Public Information Office.
If you have any questions about the material presented here, contact 
<a href="feedback.html">me (not the JPL PIO office)!</a> ***</strong>
<p></p>
<ul>
<li><a href="srl2/stat.html">Mission status</a></li>
<li><a href="srl2/perf.html">Performance updates</a></li>
<li><a href="srl2/ground.html">Ground measurements at Death Valley, California</a></li> 
<li><a href="srl2/dataproc.html">Status of data processing</a></li>
<li><a href="srl2-pkt.html">Press Kit for SRL -2</a>
</ul>
<p>
<strong>Optical views from STS-68</strong> are <a
href="http://images.jsc.nasa.gov/html/dlpao68.htm">now available from JSC</a>
 </p>
<p>
<strong><a href="jplpio.html"> Here is a link to the official SIR-C/X-SAR images from
the JPL Public Information 
Office</a></strong>.  It now contains some very nice images from SRL-2,
hot off the press!
</p>
<HR>
<p></p>
