<title>How to Obtain Additional SIR-C/X-SAR Materials</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#888800"
      background="../JPLRADAR.GIF" alink="#00FF00">

<font size=+1>

<center>
<IMG SRC = "../CEDLOGO.GIF" alt="[SIR-CED LOGO]">
<h1>
How to Obtain Additional SIR-C/X-SAR Materials
</h1>
</center>
<p>
This information sheet explains how NASA photographs, slides, mission
status information, and CD-ROMs produced by the SIR-C/X-SAR Project at the Jet
Propulsion Laboratory,  can be obtained by scientists, educators, and the
general public.   SIR-C/X-SAR is a joint US/German/Italian mission which flew
aboard the Space Shuttle Endeavour in April and October, 1994 as part of the
Space Radar Laboratory. <p>
<p>
The Space Radar Laboratory, part of NASA's Mission to Planet Earth, studied how
our global environment is changing.  From the unique vantage point of space,
SIR-C/X-SAR observed and monitored large-scale environmental processes with a
focus on climate change.  The spaceborne data, complemented by aircraft and
ground studies, give scientists highly detailed information to help them
distinguish natural environmental changes from those that are the result of
human activity.  <p>

<h2>Internet Computer Access</h2>

The Imaging Radar Group at JPL have set up a World Wide Web server site, 
which can be accessed using a browse tool such as NCSA's Mosaic. 
The URL for the site is:  
<a href="HTTP://southport.jpl.nasa.gov/companion/">
http://southport.jpl.nasa.gov/companion/</a>

The site contains up-to-date information on the imaging radar program at JPL,
radar images and results from the two SIR-C missions, sample data and videos,
information on how to get radar images and software for displaying radar
images, plus links to other Internet sites which distribute radar images,
including:<p>
<p>

The JPL Public Information Office also maintains a public access 
Internet computer site. Their URL on World Wide Web is
<a href="HTTP://www.jpl.nasa.gov/">
http://www.jpl.nasa.gov/</a>
or one can use anonymous FTP to 
jplinfo.jpl.nasa.gov (137.78.104.2).
Dial-up users via modem can connect to the site by dialing (818) 354-1333.
Parameters are:
no parity, 8 data bits, 1 stop bit.  This line supports speeds up to 14.4 kbps
with v32 bis/v42 error correction and compression protocols, and supports up to
3 callers simultaneously. <p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
For questions related to the site, please contact:
<blockquote>
Jet Propulsion Laboratory<br>
Public Information Office<br>
(818) 354-5011
</blockquote>
<p>

NASA Spacelink can be accessed via TELNET to
spacelink.msfc.nasa.gov (192.149.89.61).
By modem (205) 895-0028.<p>
<p>

The EROS Data Center, which has  SIR-C survey (low-resolution) images on-line
at the URL:
<a href="HTTP://edcwww.cr.usgs.gov/landdaac/">
http://edcwww.cr.usgs.gov/landdaac/</a>
<p>
The Italian Space Agency Internet address: asimt0.mt.asi.it or 192.106.234.2<p>
  <p>
DLR  World Wide Web address (URL):  
<a href="HTTP://129.247.162.47/">
http://129.247.162.47/</a>
<p>

<h2>Digital Data</h2>

SIR-C survey image data are available on CD-ROMs from the U.S.
Geological Survey's EROS Data Center (EDC).   The EDC is the Earth Observing
System Data and Information System (EOSDIS) Land Processes Distributed Active
Archive Center (Land Processes DAAC).  <p>
<p>
The survey data are also posted on the EDC World Wide Web site listed above.<p>
<p>
Survey data are uncalibrated, low resolution (50 m) images of entire data
takes.  One CD contains up to twelve data takes.  These data are suitable for
determining the extent of area coverage,
interpreting landforms, and for use in requesting high resolution standard
digital frame products.  SIR-C standard digital image data will be available on
8 mm tapes from the EDC in early 1995.  Standard products are data frames (50
or 100 km in length) that are calibrated and that are higher resolution (~10-45
m) than the survey products.   For information, contact: <p>

<ul>
EROS Data Center Distributed Active Archive Center (EDC DAAC)<br>
User Services<br>
Sioux Falls, South Dakota 57198<br>
Tel: (605) 594-6116<br>
Fax: (605) 594-6963<br>
Email: <a href="MAILTO:EDC@EOS.NASA.GOV">edc@eos.nasa.gov</a><br>
WWW: <a href="HTTP://edcwww.cr.usgs.gov/landdaac/">
http://edcwww.cr.usgs.gov/landdaac/
</a>
</ul>
<p>

<h2>Photographic Products</h2>

Photographic products of released images are available through the JPL
contractors listed below.   They maintain and sell a catalog of available
images which is updated periodically.  All images have captions describing the
area covered and the features of particular scientific interest.   For products
contact:<p>

<blockquote>
Newell Colour<br>
221 North Westmoreland Avenue<br>
Los Angeles, California 90004-4892<br>
(213) 380-2980, Ext 269<br>
FAX: (213) 739-6984<br>
</blockquote>

<h2>General Information</h2>

The JPL Public Information Office (PIO) provides general information
about the SIR-C/X-SAR mission.  PIO will direct specific inquiries to the
appropriate sources.  The office's  primary responsibility is to provide
materials to the working press. Contact information:<p>

<blockquote>
Jet Propulsion Laboratory<br>
Public Information Office<br>
Mail Stop 186-120<br>
4800 Oak Grove Drive<br>
Pasadena, California 91109<br>
(818) 354-5011<br>
FAX: (818) 354-4537<br>
</blockquote>

<h2>Videos</h2>

Videotapes of  SIR-C materials can be purchased from:<p>
<blockquote>
MediaTech<br>
10523-45  Burbank Blvd.<br>
North Hollywood, California 91601<br>
(818) 753-3058<br>
FAX: (818) 985-1013<br>
</blockquote>

Copies can be produced in a variety of video formats and standards,
including PAL and SECAM.  The following videos are available:<p>
<ul type=circle>
<li><b>AVC-94-144</b> "SIR-C/X-SAR STS-59 COMPUTER ANIMATION COLLECTION -
4/18/94;"  (0:19:21)
<li><b>AVC-94-184</b> "SIR-C/X-SAR 1ST FLIGHT RESULTS - 7/5/94;"  (0:04:12)
<li><b>AVC-95-021</b> "SIR-C/X-SAR  STS-68 COMPUTER ANIMATION
	COLLECTION - 11/18/94;"  (0:51:00)
<li><b>AVC-95-038</b> "SIR-C/X-SAR  FLIGHT 1 &AMP;  2 HIGHLIGHTS" 
(no narration or text accompanies images) - 11/08/94;  (0:04:55)
</ul>

<h2>SIR-CED Educational CD-ROMS</h2>

<b>SIR-CED </b>is an education initiative designed for middle school and high
school students.  A pre-launch CD-ROM (Volume ID SIRCED01)  contains a
Teacher's Guide, radar images, photographs from the Space shuttle, ground-based
photographs, and  maps  of sites all around the world which were imaged by the
SIR-C mission. The Teachers' Guide and Lesson Plans from SIR-CED are on-line at
a World Wide Web site known as AskEric, maintained by Syracuse University, at
URL: 
<a href="HTTP://ericir.syr.edu/">
http://ericir.syr.edu/</a>
<p>
A second, post-flight SIR-CED CD-ROM (SIRCED03) containing data from the 
two SIR-C/X-SAR
missions is now available for both the IBM-PC and Macintosh computers. 
To request copies of the SIR-CED CDs, contact the
EROS Data Center at the address listed above, or:<p>

<blockquote>
NASA Central Operation of Resources for Educators (CORE)<br>
Lorain County JVS<br>
15181 Route 58 South<br>
Oberlin, Ohio 44074<br>
Tel: (216) 774-1051 (ext. 293/294)<br>
Fax: (216) 774-2144<br>
</blockquote>

<h2>Teacher Resource Centers</h2>

NASA's Education Division supports Teacher Resource Centers (TRCs) at
each NASA Center, as well as a large number of Regional TRCs in cooperation
with educational organizations around the country.  It also supports a national
center for distribution of audio-visual materials, known as NASA CORE (address
above).  <p>
<p>
The TRC at NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory (JPL) has a wide variety of
planetary material available for teachers.  The JPL TRC has compiled a video
collection, which is updated periodically. For information on titles/contents,
and other services, contact: <p>

<blockquote>
Jet Propulsion Laboratory<br>
Teacher Resource Center<br>
Mail Stop CS-530<br>
4800 Oak Grove Drive<br>
Pasadena, California 91109<br>
(818) 354-6916<br>
</blockquote>

Footnote:
The Spaceborne Imaging Radar-C mission is managed by NASA's Jet Propulsion
Laboratory (JPL) in Pasadena, California.

<P>

