<TITLE>Ground Measurements</TITLE>
<H1>Ground Measurements</H1>
<HR>
<P></P>
In order to calibrate the radar data, scietists and engineers 
 have deployed calibration
targets at sites around the world.  At Death Valley, California, we
placed <a href="../gif/Reflectr.gif"><strong>corner reflectors</strong>
<em> (108k)</em></a> and <a
href="../gif/LPARC.gif"><strong>transponders</strong><em> (72k)</em></a> 
on flat level areas near Stovepipe
Wells.</p>
<p>Corner reflectors have a known radar brightness.  Therefore, during
calibration of the data, we compare the measured brightness of the
corner reflector with the theoretical brightness to obtain the
calibration offset.  The radar data is then corrected by this factor.
The phase between polarizations, and the relative amplitudes, may be
similarly corrected.  A typical radar signature of a corner reflector
looks like <a href="../gif/Impulse.gif"><strong>this</strong> <em>(99k)</em></a>.</p>
<p>Transponders receive the radar  signal and amplify and retransmit it
back to the radar.  These devices may also be used during
calibration.</p>
<p>At Death Valley, a team also deployed <a href="../gif/RCVR.gif">
<strong>ground receivers and
transmitters</strong><em>(108k)</em></a>.  
These devices were used to measure the antenna gain
pattern and offsets between different channels in the along track
direction.  They will also be used during SRL-2 to measure attenuation
of the radar signal by rainforest canopies.</p>
<HR>
