<title>Project Status Report</title>
<hr>

<h2>Project updates 8,9,10</h2>
<h3>
SIR-C/X-SAR STATUS REPORT FOR THE PERIOD ENDING
DAY 8:0 HRS TO DAY 9:0 HRS MISSION ELAPSED TIME
</h3>
<p>
The interferometry imaging activities began 5 hours into the day with
Data Take 118.1. Activities have proceeded according to plan
throughout this period without any significant issues. A total of 107
SIR-C tapes and 25 X-SAR tapes have been recorded.
</p><p>
Images of the oil slick along with full and close coverage images of
KSC were received for press release. A SIR-C calibration update was
received and the system has continued to be stable in terms of channel
amplitude and phase balances. The cross talk between horizontal and
vertical polarizations has remained low. To date, 3 image frames with
corner reflectors and 6 without have been analyzed and calibrated

</p><p>
ANOMALIES- One tape threading and one tape loading anomaly occurred.


</p><p>
<hr>
<h3>
SIR-C/X-SAR STATUS REPORT FOR THE PERIOD ENDING
DAY 9:0 HRS TO DAY 10:0 HRS MISSION ELAPSED TIME
</h3>
<p>
SUMMARY-The interferometry imaging activities have proceeded according
to plan throughout this period . A total of 129 SIR-C tapes and 31
X-SAR tapes have been recorded.

</p><p>
Early indications are that the one day repeat targeting is
exceptionally accurate. A top of the orbit pass over Canada covering
some 200km had a repeat pass separation on the order of 70 m. Other
passes throughout the day averaged about 200 m separation.

</p><p>
Activity in the data procesing coninues at an intense  pace. Images of
Moscow, San Francisco, Otzal, the Weddell Sea and others are being
prepared for release. A topgraphic map of Mammoth is being prepared.
An image of Mammoth, Mt. was processed on the  Cray T3D supercomputer
at JPL as a (successful)  experiment.  A joint Italian/German team
working at DLR in Oberpfaffenhofen, Germany has been working to
prepare interferometric SAR products .

</p><p>
ANOMALIES-

</p><p>
7 hours into the day, PHRR 1 began to exhibit high error rates.
Subsequent data playback tests from this recorder indicated it was
failing to record properly. All SIR-C recording was switched over to
PHRR 2. Since the last playback from that recorder occurred some 12
hours prior to the failed playback, all the data takes recorded since
then are suspect. Of the 29 repeat pass targets imaged during the PHRR
1 suspect performance period only 3 will be lost in the event that
data cannot be recovered from the tapes. PHRR 1 will be replaced by
the spare at the start of day 10.

</p><p>
8 hours 33 minutes into the day, C-band center leaf panel #2 failed in
the same manner as #6 causing loss of the V-pol transmitters within
the panel. As a consequence of these two failures, 1db of SNR will be
lost from the typical 10-15db of SNR for C band V-pol data. Adequate
performance margin still remains to accomplish the required imaging
science.


</p><p>
<hr>
<h3>
SIR-C/X-SAR STATUS REPORT FOR THE PERIOD ENDING
DAY 10:0 HRS TO DAY11:0 HRS MISSION ELAPSED TIME
</h3><p>

SUMMARY-The interferometry imaging activities have proceeded according
to plan throughout this period . A total of 155 SIR-C tapes and 36
X-SAR tapes have been recorded, nearly 25 more than STS-59.

</p><p>
Activity in data processing continues at an intense pace. X-SAR images
recently released or planned for release include: Baikal Lake in
Russia; Mende, France(STS 59-68 seasonal change); Kennedy Space
Center, Florida: Oetztal, Austria (STS-59-68 seasonal change); and
Kilauea, Hawaii (3 dimensional and fringe images from STS 59-68 data).
SIR-C images for release include: Long Valley , California
(3-dimensional view); Kilauea, Hawaii (deformation map);,and possibly
Fort Irwin, California (L and C band interferogram comparisons).

</p><p>
The decision as made to extend the interferometry phase of the mission
to recapture some data takes which may have been lost due to the
malfunctioning PHRR 1. After that, the orbits will be allowed to
gradually diverge to extend the interferometry baseline. Operations
will be shut down in 18 hrs as part of the preparation for the deorbit
mission phase.


</p><p>
ANOMALIES-

</p><p>
After replacing PHRR 1 with the spare PHRR, the new PHRR 1 exhibited
high bit errors on playback. A special cross play test was conducted
at MET 009/18:56 using PHRR 1 recorded data for playback on PHRR 2.
Results were that PHRR 1 was recording properly. The cross playback
errors at 45 MHZ were, however, higher than the other recorders. This
could force some special efforts to be employed to recover the
recorded data on the ground. Use of PHRR 1 will be minimized in the
future due to this situation.

</p>

<hr>
