<title>Project Status Report</title>
<hr>
<h3>
Good news!  SRL-2 is back in nominal operating mode.
As of MET 05/21:30:00 full vernier jet attitude control
was re-established.  The affected portion of the timeline
is from 05/06:49 to 05/21:30.  Most datatakes were
unsuccessful during this period, although efforts appear
to have been successful to obtain quality data on DT 88.2
(Kliuchevskoi April/October comparison) and DT 96.2
(North Sea intentional oil slick experiment).  As soon
as the MET clock rolls over to Day 6, we will forward
a report of datatakes acquired during the vernier anomaly.
</h3>
Jeff

<hr>
 <h2>SIR-C/X-SAR MISSION STATUS REPORT FOR THE PERIOD
  DAY 5: 0 HRS TO DAY 6: 0 HRS, MISSION ELAPSED TIME</h2>
<p></p>
SUMMARY- Normal data taking operations were interrupted for
approximately fourteen hours due to a malfunctioning sensor in one of
the Orbiter's vernier thrusters. The alternative attitude control
options could support degraded data taking operations, but only at a
large increase in propellant consumption. The decision was made to
suspend any attempts to take data in a routine manner, allow the
orbiter to operate in a wide attitude control dead band and take data
for super sites only. It is unlikely that the data acquired under
these conditions (ten degree dead band) are easily processable or
correctly targetted.
<p></p>
     The only exception to this strategy was a period of time when the
orbiter was operated under a new strategy that allowed operation of
the verniers, but under a very carefully managed set of conditions
that could also lead to a large use of propellant. The data acquired
under these conditions was in support of an experiment conducted by
Germany in the North Sea to measure the radar signature of different
weight and types of oils released into the North Sea under carefully
controlled and monitored conditions. This experiment had been delayed
by one day due to high wind conditions. The data were returned in real
time, processed and found to be highly useful.
<p></p>
     All told, approximately three per cent of the mission's planned
data takes were affected with significantly less impact to the science
due both to the redundant data take strategy for the mission timeline
and the possibility of operating for an eleventh day.
<p></p>
     Data processing continues to be very exciting. Scenes show very
clearly recent  mud flows from Mt. Pinatubo. Data have been acquired
which can be used to examine several other volcanoes for recent
changes. The interferometry data from the day four, Mammoth Mt.,
California data take have been processed into perspective scenes, a
high resolution Digital Elevation Model and a contour terrain map.
<p></p>
<p></p>
ANOMALIES- Several instances of tape cassette load problems were noted
in the PHRR. 
</p>

<hr>
</body></html>
